Tutorial 1 - Learning The Rust Package Manager Cargo

6 steps

Rust is truly a game-changer, empowering developers to build and test their own software with ease, without the hassle of juggling too many tools for different systems. And guess what? The Rust ecosystem is booming, with a plethora of crates just waiting to be explored!

In this tutorial, you'll learn how to wield cargo to elevate your Rust developer journey to new heights! 🚀

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the 🆘 | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.

NOTE: Getting rewards from this quest is over as it was only applicable on the Earn app when it was part of a campaign. Therefore, submissions are not reviewed or are disabled. However, you are highly encouraged to still complete the quest to practice your understanding.

Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Recommended to have some Rust knowledge, specifically:

  • Basic understanding of Rust syntax and semantics
  • Variables and data types
  • Functions and return types
  • Familiarity of Option and Result for Error Handling

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Use the Rust ecosystem with Cargo
  • Apply Rust project structures in different situations
  • Learn how to use cargo to manage projects

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Exploring the Ecosystem with crates.io

    Rust has a centralised registry for the community called https://crates.io. You can publish your crates, look for cool projects, and get information and statistics of various projects.

    Try visiting the website and explore around and see some cool crates and even some obscure ones.

  • Step 2: Installing Cargo with Rustup

    If you followed the previous campaign Empower Your Developer Journey with Rust and already installed rustup, you can skip this step. However, if you haven’t, you can follow the steps that are linked to https://rustup.rs/.

    You might want to click the link pointed by the red-arrow like from the screenshot below if your operating system is not detected

    If clicked, it will drop down to show other installers like the screenshot below

    For those who like to develop software on a Linux system but still want to use Windows as a daily productivity operating system, you can follow the instructions from https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/install. Once WSL is installed, you can just follow the instructions in https://rustup.rs for Linux systems and run those commands within your WSL instance.

  • Step 3: Cargo as a package manager

    Cargo is Rust’s package manager. It allows us to install and manage project dependencies called crates. But we can also use it to install third-party software like any other package manager similar to a Linux distribution’s system package manager, brew, or Window’s winget tool.

    Commonly used cargo commands

    Cargo simplifies the process of building, testing, and benchmarking Rust software by abstracting away the necessary commands through the Rust compiler, rustc. These commands include cargo build and cargo test.

    Cargo Build

    When you run cargo build, it compiles your project by default with debug symbols. These symbols are invaluable for debugging, as they provide detailed information to track down bugs. However, keep in mind that debug symbols increase the size of the compiled binary or library. Additionally, cargo build typically applies minimal optimizations. To enable a fully optimised build, simply add the --release flag. This will have the full command as follows

    cargo build --release

    Cargo Test and Why Tests Are Important

    The cargo test command is used to execute all unit tests within your Rust project. It automatically discovers and runs any functions annotated with #[test]. This enables you to ensure that your code behaves as expected, catching any regressions or errors as you develop.

    #[test]
fn test_addition() {
    assert_eq!(2 + 2, 4);
}
    Rust

    From the example code snippet above, we have a function named test_addition. The #[test] annotation indicates that this function is a unit test. Inside the function, we use the assert_eq! macro to compare the result of the addition operation (2 + 2) with the expected value of 4. If the assertion fails, the test will fail, indicating that there is a problem in the code.

    Testing is crucial in software development for several reasons. Firstly, it ensures that the code behaves as expected, helping to identify and fix bugs early in the development process. This not only improves the quality of the software but also reduces the likelihood of encountering issues in production.

    Testing also provides a safety net when making changes to the codebase. Developers can run tests to verify that their modifications haven't introduced regressions or unintended side effects. This promotes confidence in making changes and enables teams to iterate on their code more rapidly.

    Moreover, testing encourages better code design and architecture. Writing tests often requires breaking down the code into smaller, testable units, which can lead to cleaner, more modular code. Additionally, writing tests forces developers to think about edge cases and error scenarios, resulting in more robust and resilient software.

    In summary, testing is important because it:

    1. Identifies and fixes bugs early
    2. Provides a safety net for code changes
    3. Encourages better code design and architecture
    4. Increases confidence in the software's reliability and stability

    More about Cargo

    For further information about other cargo commands, try running cargo help.

  • Step 4: Installing some cool tools with Cargo

    Cargo also has another subcommand called install. This subcommand will install binaries from a project if there are and fails if it does not contain or compile binaries. For example, trying to “install” a library will give us the following error below.

    Let’s try installing bat by running the following command

    cargo install bat

    This command will install bat into the default CARGO_HOME directory. As detailed in the Cargo Book:

    By default, these are stored under $HOME/.cargo (%USERPROFILE%.cargo on Windows), but this variable overrides the location of this directory.
    -

    Once bat is installed and CARGO_HOME/bin is included in your PATH (or Path for Windows), you can seamlessly use bat to inspect your file contents right from your terminal. It supports syntax highlighting right out of the box as shown in the screenshot below.

    Do keep in mind that some of the projects are not cross-platform so some projects might not work on your operating system.

  • Step 5: Project Management with Cargo and Initialising Our Banking System Project

    Initialising our first Rust project

    Now that we already know some commonly used commands with cargo, we can start setting up our Rust project for Quest 2. Run the following command in your terminal.

    cargo new banking-system

    The command will create and initialise a new Rust project with default layout. The created Rust project will be our first Rust project for this campaign! 👀

    Now, change your directory to the root of your newly created project. The contents of your project should be something like the diagram below

    When you run subcommands like cargo build or cargo test in the root directory of your project where the Cargo.toml file resides, Cargo will create a Cargo.lock file and a target directory containing cached build data. The Cargo.lock file captures a snapshot of the dependencies and other data required for a successful build, allowing for reproducibility.

    While this caching mechanism helps reduce compilation time by rebuilding only necessary data, it can also introduce inaccuracies or "dirt" over time. In such cases, simply removing the cache using cargo cleancan provide a fresh start for your compilation process.

    Project structure

    For now, our project will follow the “traditional” default project layout. The following diagram shows what it looks like. The project “root” represents the top-most level directory.

    A traditional layout can either be

    • a binary target (the default)
    • a library target  
    • it can be both assuming you have the files lib.rs and main.rs 

    However, the last one is done manually e.g. adding a lib.rs file after the default project layout was created, otherwise, we will get an error if we force it like below.
